  "prompt": "Why do bolts and nuts not get welded, when both are the same metal and their crystal structure is the same?",
  "response": "Bolts and nuts are typically not welded together for several reasons, despite being made of the same metal and having similar crystal structures. Here are the key factors:\n\n1. **Functionality**: Bolts and nuts are designed to provide a clamping force and allow for ease of disassembly. Welding would create a permanent joint, defeating the purpose of having a fastening system that can be easily removed and adjusted.\n\n2. **Heat Affected Zone**: Welding involves melting the base materials and often changing the heat-affected zone properties. This can introduce residual stresses and potentially weaken the materials in the vicinity of the weld, leading to issues such as brittleness or reduced fatigue resistance.\n\n3. **Precision and Tolerance**: Fastening systems like bolts and nuts are manufactured to tight tolerances. Welding can create thermal distortions that can interfere with the fit and function of the assembly.\n\n4. **Strength and Load Distribution**: Bolts and nuts rely on the principles of friction and clamping force to distribute loads effectively. A welded joint may not provide the same load distribution characteristics, which can lead to failure under load.\n\n5. **Corrosion Issues**: Welding can lead to localized heating and cooling, which can change the microstructure and potentially lead to corrosion issues. Bolted connections can be designed with protective coatings and have the ability to replace individual components if they corrode without affecting the entire assembly.\n\n6. **Manufacturing Practices**: From a manufacturing standpoint, welding requires additional considerations like joint preparation, fit-up, and post-weld treatments. Bolting is often simpler and more efficient for assembly in many applications.\n\nIn summary, while bolts and nuts may be made from similar materials, the functional requirements, mechanical properties, and practical considerations all favor the use of mechanical fastening methods rather than welding.",
